Volumes, the basics.

A pod declares a list of volumes, under the spec volumes field. Then each container mounts any of those volumes, under volume mounts. And the link between the two is by name.

So in a manifest, a container has a volume mount that names scratch, at a mount path. And the pod has a volume, also named scratch, whose type is empty dir. The names match, and that is the connection.

Two things to internalise.

First, the volume is declared on the pod, but mounted into the container. That is exactly how multiple containers share a volume. The sidecar pattern from notebook two. Both containers declare a volume mount referencing the same volume name.

Second, a volume type is a single key under the volume entry. Empty dir, host path, config map, secret, or persistent volume claim. Each volume entry uses exactly one of these type keys.

The mount itself supports a few useful knobs. Read only true mounts it read only. Sub path mounts only a sub path of the volume, which is the doesn't live update gotcha from notebook five. And mount propagation is for advanced cases like see-ess-eye drivers, rarely set by hand.

The volume types fall into two big groups. Ephemeral, which live with the pod. And persistent, which outlive the pod, backed by a persistent volume. The rest of this module walks both. On our map, a volume is the wire between a pod and whatever backs it. Either an ephemeral scratch space, or the durable storage box below.
